1️⃣ Prototype (Shared by All Objects)
Example:
                            function Person(name) {
                                this.name = name;
                            }
                            
                            Person.prototype.sayHello = function() {
                                console.log("Hello " + this.name);
                            };

What happened?
sayHello is stored once
All Person objects share it
Memory efficient

📦 Memory Structure
p1 ---> Person.prototype ---> sayHello()


2️⃣ Static (Belongs to the Class Itself)
Example:
                          function Person(name) {
                              this.name = name;
                          }

                          Person.species = "Homo Sapiens";

Usage:                   console.log(Person.species);  // Homo Sapiens

❌ Not accessible via object:
                          const p1 = new Person("Sam");
                          console.log(p1.species);  // undefined

ES6 Version (Cleaner Syntax)
                                  class Person {
                                      static species = "Homo Sapiens";
                                  
                                      constructor(name) {
                                          this.name = name;
                                      }
                                  
                                      sayHello() {
                                          console.log("Hello " + this.name);
                                      }
                                  }

When To Use What?
✅ Use Prototype When:
Function depends on instance data
Example: getAge(), sayHello()

✅ Use Static When:
Function doesn’t depend on instance
Utility methods
Global counters
Constants

Why not put everything static?
Because: Static methods don’t have access to instance properties (this.name). They aren’t inherited by objects

Why not put everything in constructor?
Because: Each object gets its own copy. Wastes memory
