JS inheritance is a little different from classical languages like Java or C++, because JS uses prototypal inheritance.

Modern Way (ES6 Class Syntax). Much cleaner.
                                class Person {
                                    constructor(name) {
                                        this.name = name;
                                    }
                                
                                    sayHello() {
                                        console.log("Hello " + this.name);
                                    }
                                }
Child class:
                                  class Student extends Person {
                                      constructor(name, grade) {
                                          super(name);  // calls parent constructor
                                          this.grade = grade;
                                      }
                                  
                                      study() {
                                          console.log(this.name + " is studying");
                                      }
                                  }

const s1 = new Student("Sam", "A");
s1.sayHello();  // inherited
s1.study();     // own method

What Does extends Do?
Behind the scenes:
Student.prototype.__proto__ = Person.prototype;
So it creates the same prototype chain as manual version.

What Does super() Do?
Inside child constructor:
super(name);
It calls the parent constructor.
If you don’t call super() before using this, JS throws error.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Method Overriding
Overriding means: Child class provides its own version of a parent method.
👇 Example
                          class Person {
                              greet() {
                                  console.log("Hello from Person");
                              }
                          }
                          
                          class Student extends Person {
                              greet() {
                                  console.log("Hello from Student");
                              }
                          }
const s1 = new Student();
s1.greet(); // Hello from Student
Because JS finds greet() in Student.prototype first and stops there.That’s overriding.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Using super in Methods
Sometimes you want: Use parent logic + add extra behavior.
Example:
                                            class Person {
                                                greet() {
                                                    console.log("Hello");
                                                }
                                            }
                                            
                                            class Student extends Person {
                                                greet() {
                                                    super.greet();  // call parent version
                                                    console.log("I am a student");
                                                }
                                            }

Output:
Hello
I am a student

🔹 Important
super.method() works only inside class methods.
Behind the scenes it basically calls:        Person.prototype.greet.call(this);
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Multiple Inheritance in JS?
Short answer: ❌ JavaScript does NOT support multiple inheritance.
You cannot do:
class A {}
class B {}
class C extends A, B {}  // ❌ Not allowed

But… you can simulate it using:
✅ Mixins
Example:
                        const canStudy = {
                            study() {
                                console.log("Studying...");
                            }
                        };
                        
                        const canPlay = {
                            play() {
                                console.log("Playing...");
                            }
                        };

                        class Student {}
                        Object.assign(Student.prototype, canStudy, canPlay);
                        
                        const s1 = new Student();
                        s1.study();
                        s1.play();

This copies methods into the prototype.
That’s how JS handles “multiple behavior”.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Composition vs Inheritance (Very Important)

🟢 Inheritance (IS-A relationship)
                                class Animal {}
                                class Dog extends Animal {}
Dog IS-A Animal.
Inheritance creates tight coupling.


Composition (HAS-A relationship)
Instead of inheriting:
                            class Engine {
                                start() {
                                    console.log("Engine started");
                                }
                            }
                            
                            class Car {
                                constructor() {
                                    this.engine = new Engine();
                                }
                            
                                startCar() {
                                    this.engine.start();
                                }
                            }
Car HAS-A Engine.More flexible.

Why Composition Is Preferred
Inheritance problems:
Deep hierarchy
Hard to modify
Tight coupling
Fragile base class problem

Composition benefits:
More modular
Easier to change behavior
Cleaner architecture
Preferred in modern JS frameworks
Most modern design patterns favor: Composition over Inheritance

