An event listener in JavaScript is used to detect when something happens in the browser and run a function in response.
Examples of events:
                  clicking a button
                  typing in an input
                  hovering over an element
                  submitting a form
                  pressing a key
JavaScript listens for these events and executes code when they occur.

1️⃣ Basic syntax
element.addEventListener("event", function);
Example:
        button.addEventListener("click", myFunction);
Meaning:
          When the button is clicked
          run myFunction()


2️⃣ Simple example
HTML:
        <button id="btn">Click me</button>
JavaScript:
          const btn = document.getElementById("btn");
          
          btn.addEventListener("click", function(){
              alert("Button clicked!");
          });


Common events:- 
    Event                           	When it happens

    click	                              mouse click
   mouseover	                          mouse hover
    mouseout	                          mouse leaves
    keydown	                            key pressed
    submit	                            form submitted
    input	                            user types in input

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Event Progression - Event bubbling, Event Capture, Event Delegation..........
1️⃣ Event Bubbling
Event bubbling means an event starts from the target element and moves upward through its ancestors.
Example HTML
            <div id="parent">
                <button id="child">Click me</button>
            </div>
JavaScript
            document.getElementById("parent").addEventListener("click", () => {
                console.log("Parent clicked");
            });
            
            document.getElementById("child").addEventListener("click", () => {
                console.log("Button clicked");
            });
What happens when the button is clicked
Button clicked
Parent clicked

Why?
Because the event bubbles upward.
Event flow
            button
               ↓
            parent div
               ↓
            body
               ↓
            document
-------------------------------------------------------
Event capturing
Event capturing is the opposite direction.
Events start at the top of the DOM and move down to the target.
Normally browsers use bubbling by default.
To enable capturing:
          parent.addEventListener("click", handler, true);
The third parameter true activates capture phase.

-------------------------------------------------------
event.stopPropagation()
stopPropagation() stops the event from continuing its path.
Example:
          child.addEventListener("click", (e) => {
              e.stopPropagation();
              console.log("Button clicked");
          });
Now clicking the button prints:     Button clicked
The event does not reach the parent.
So bubbling stops.
---------------------------------------------------------
preventDefault()
Some HTML elements have default browser behavior.
Examples:

      Element	             Default behavior
      link <a>	        navigate to another page
        form	           submit and reload page
      checkbox	            toggle check
   button in form	          submit form

preventDefault() stops that behavior.
------------------------------------------------------

2️⃣ Event Delegation
Event delegation means attaching one event listener to a parent instead of many child elements.
Event delegation is a coding technique that uses event bubbling to handle events more efficiently.
Instead of adding event listeners to many child elements, you attach one listener to the parent.
This is very useful when there are many similar elements.
Example
HTML:
              <ul id="menu">
                  <li>Home</li>
                  <li>Profile</li>
                  <li>Settings</li>
              </ul>

JavaScript:
              document.getElementById("menu").addEventListener("click", (event) => {
                  console.log(event.target.textContent);
              });
What happens
When a user clicks:
Profile
Console prints:
Profile
Even though the listener is on ul, the click works for all li elements.

Why developers use this
Instead of:
          li1.addEventListener(...)
          li2.addEventListener(...)
          li3.addEventListener(...)
You write one listener.
This improves performance.


3️⃣ removeEventListener
Sometimes you want to stop listening to an event.
That’s what removeEventListener() does.
Example
          function sayHello(){
              console.log("Hello");
          }
          const btn = document.querySelector("button");
          btn.addEventListener("click", sayHello);

Now remove it:
          btn.removeEventListener("click", sayHello);

Now clicking the button does nothing.
Important rule
removeEventListener only works if the same function reference is used.

This works:
            btn.addEventListener("click", sayHello);
            btn.removeEventListener("click", sayHello);

This does NOT work:
            btn.addEventListener("click", () => console.log("Hi"));
            btn.removeEventListener("click", () => console.log("Hi"));
Because they are different functions.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Real-world application examples
1️⃣ Dropdown menus
Click inside dropdown → stop propagation so menu doesn't close.

            dropdown.addEventListener("click", (e) => {
               e.stopPropagation();
            });

2️⃣ Form validation
Prevent form submission until validation passes.

              form.addEventListener("submit", (e) => {
                 e.preventDefault();
              });

3️⃣ Event delegation in large lists
Used in dashboards, chat apps, task lists.
              
              list.addEventListener("click", (e) => {
                 if(e.target.matches(".delete")){
                     e.target.parentElement.remove();
                 }
              });
Only one listener handles all items.

4️⃣ Modal dialogs
Click outside modal → close it.
Click inside modal → stop propagation so it doesn't close.

Most real-world apps use:
event bubbling (for event delegation)
preventDefault (forms, links)
stopPropagation (modals, dropdowns)
Capturing is rarely used unless needed for special control.

































































